4.3 Update An Application Menus
Lesson
Application menus organize related modules in ServiceNow's navigation panel, helping users quickly access the functionality they need. Modules are the individual menu items within an application menu that link to specific pages, lists, forms, or other content.

Creating a new application menu:
- Navigate to All > System Definition > Application Menus.
- Select New and complete the required details (name, description).
- Save to add modules immediately, or Submit to return to the list.

Creating modules within an application:
- Open the application menu record.
- Navigate to the Modules related list.
- Select New to create and associate a module with the application menu.
- Configure the module's Title, Order (determines position in menu), and Link Type (what happens when selected).

Scenario
Your HHD table and form configurations are complete, and the Service Desk team is ready to start creating device records. However, they've reported that the navigation isn't intuitive—there's no quick way to create a new HHD record without going through the list view first.

Your task is to create a "Create New" module that allows users to quickly open a blank HHD form, and rename the existing list module to improve clarity for end users.

Task Objectives
1. Access and edit an existing application menu using the Edit Application icon.

2. Create a new module within  the HHD application menu:
- Title: Create New
- Application menu: HHD
- Order: 100

3. Configure a module's Link Type to open a new record form:
- Link type: New Record
- Table: Holographic Handheld HHD [u_cmdb_ci_hardware_hhd]

4. Verify that menu changes are immediately reflected in the navigation panel
4.4 Add Access controls
Lesson
Roles in ServiceNow are collections of permissions that control what users can see and do within the platform. They act as security containers that grant access to specific applications, modules, tables, records, and functionality. Instead of assigning permissions to individual users, administrators assign roles, making security management scalable and consistent.

Roles ensure users only access what they need for their job functions, following the principle of least privilege. They create clear boundaries between different teams and responsibilities (IT staff vs. HR staff vs. managers). Assigning a single role grants multiple permissions at once, rather than configuring access individually. Role-based access control (RBAC) helps meet regulatory requirements by documenting who can access sensitive data.

Scenario
Your organization has deployed a new custom application called "HHD" (Holographic Handheld Devices) to track specialized hardware in the CMDB. During the initial table creation, ServiceNow automatically generated the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role and associated access controls. However, the application was initially configured with the itil role, which grants access to all IT staff.

Your task is to restrict access so that only users assigned the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role can see and use the HHD application and its modules.

Task Objectives
1. Verify you see the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user.

2. Add the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to the HHD application and remove the itil role.

3. Modify each of the HHD modules to add the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to each of the modules (removing the itil role).
4.5 Grant Role To support Groups
Lesson
In ServiceNow, groups provide an efficient way to manage role assignments for multiple users simultaneously. Rather than assigning roles to individual users one at a time, administrators can assign roles to groups, and all members of those groups automatically inherit the assigned roles.

Scenario
Your organization has successfully created the HHD (Holographic Handheld Devices) application and configured role-based access controls. The u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role has been created and applied to the application menu and modules, but there's a problem: no users can actually access the HHD application yet!

The development team forgot to assign the new role to the support groups that need it. The Service Desk and Training Technology Support teams are responsible for managing HHD devices, but they currently lack the necessary role to view or work with the HHD application.
Your task is to grant the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to both support groups so their members can begin working with holographic handheld devices in ServiceNow.

Task Objectives
1. Add the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to the Service Desk group.

2. Add the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to the Training Technology Support group

4.6 Test Visibility Settings
Lesson
User impersonation is a critical administrative function in ServiceNow that allows administrators to view the platform exactly as another user would see it. This capability is essential for troubleshooting access issues, verifying role-based permissions, and ensuring that security configurations are working as intended. By impersonating users, you can confirm that application visibility and functionality align with assigned roles and group memberships without needing to log in as that user or modify your own permissions temporarily.

Scenario
The u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role has recently been added to specific support groups to grant access to the Holographic Handheld Device (HHD) application. As an administrator, you need to verify that access controls are working properly. Users who belong to the HHD support groups should see the application and its modules, while users outside those groups should not have access, even if they have other roles like itil.

Your task is to impersonate two users with different access levels and confirm the application visibility is configured correctly.

Task Objectives

