4.7 Establish Access Control Rules
Lesson
Access Control Lists (ACLs) are the foundation of data security in ServiceNow. They define who can perform specific operations (create, read, update, delete) on tables and fields. While application menus and modules control what users can see in the interface, ACLs control what data users can actually access and manipulate. In this simulation, you'll learn to create granular access controls that restrict incident records based on business requirements, ensuring that only authorized users can work with sensitive HHD-related incidents.

Scenario
Your organization has successfully configured the HHD application interface and assigned the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role to support groups. However, there's a critical security gap: while the HHD application menu is hidden from most users, IT staff with the itil role can still see ALL incidents in the system—including HHD incidents—when they navigate to incident lists.

This creates a problem. HHD incidents contain sensitive information about holographic handheld devices that should only be accessible to specialized support teams (Service Desk and Training Technology Support), not the entire IT organization.

Your task is to elevate your security privileges and create three Access Control rules on the Incident table that restrict read, write, and create operations for HHD incidents. These rules will ensure that only users with the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role can access incidents where the Service Offering is "Infinity (HHD)".

Task Objectives
1. Elevate the admin role to security_admin.

Note: You will be creating 3 ACL records on the Incident table for the u_holographic_hhd_user role.

2. Create a new ACL record with the following filled in:
- Type: Record (keep default)
- Operation: read
- Admin overrides: selected
- Active: selected
- Name: Incident [incident]
- Description: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role required to read HHD incident records.
- Role: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user

3. Under the Data Condition section, add a  filter condition:
- Service offering | is | Infinity (HHD)

Note: When the first new ACL record is populated, Save the record, select Continue. Once it is saved, you will return to that same ACL record.

4. Verify Security Rules and Update the form as follows (you will use Insert and Stay to populate the form again).

5. Verify Security Rules and use Insert and Stay to update the form with the following: 
- Operation: write
- Description: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role required to write HHD incident records.
- Role: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user
- Data Condition: Service offering | is | Infinity (HHD) (auto-fills)
- Verify Security Rules and Insert and Stay.

6. Verify Security Rules and use Insert and Stay to update the form with the following:
-  Operation: create
- Description: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user role required to create HHD incident records.
- Role: u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user
- Data Condition: Service offering | is | Infinity (HHD) (auto-fills)
- Verify Security Rules and update the record.
4.8 Create a new ACL
Lesson
While table-level Access Control Lists (ACLs) protect entire records, field-level ACLs provide granular security for individual columns within those records. This fine-grained control is essential when certain fields contain sensitive data that requires additional protection beyond general table access. In this simulation, you'll learn to create a specialized role and apply it to a field-level ACL, ensuring that only authorized users can modify a specific field while others can still work with the rest of the record.

Scenario
Your organization is preparing to import a batch of HHD (Holographic Handheld Device) records into the system. Each device has a unique asset tag number that serves as its official identifier for inventory tracking, financial reporting, and compliance purposes.

The problem: If members of the Service Desk and Training Technology Support groups can edit the Asset tag field, accidental changes or typos could create serious inventory discrepancies, financial audit failures, and compliance violations. Asset tags should only be modified by a specialized asset management team who follow strict procedures.
However, you still want the support teams to create and update other fields on HHD records (like location, assignment, or status)—just not the Asset tag field.

Your task is to create a new role called u_hhd_asset_tagger and configure a field-level write ACL on the Asset tag field that requires this specialized role, effectively locking the field from modification by general support staff while keeping the rest of the record editable.

Task Objectives
1. With the elevated security_admin role, create a new role with the following:
- Name: u_hhd_asset_tagger
- Application: Global

2. Navigate to the list of Access Control (ACL), and filter the list of rules for u_cmdb_ci_hardware_hhd with the write operation.

3. Locate the Name field and select Holographic Handheld HHD [u_cmdb_ci_hardware_hhd], then select Asset tag field creating tag as asset tag.

4. Insert and stay, then add u_hhd_asset_tagger under Required roles.

5. Update the Description field with, "Asset Tagger access control on u_cmdb_ci_hardware_hhd"
4.8 Grant a Role for Tagging
Lesson
Groups in ServiceNow serve as containers for organizing users who share common responsibilities and access requirements. By assigning roles to groups rather than individual users, administrators create scalable, maintainable access control structures. When combined with field-level ACLs, groups enable precise delegation of specialized tasks to specific teams or individuals. In this simulation, you'll create a purpose-built group for asset tag management and assign the appropriate role and membership.

Scenario
You've successfully created the u_hhd_asset_tagger role and configured a field-level ACL that restricts write access to the Asset tag field on HHD records. However, the role currently has no users assigned to it, which means nobody—not even the intended asset manager—can update asset tags.

Your organization has identified Annette Frietas as the designated asset manager for HHD devices. She's responsible for maintaining accurate asset tag records, performing physical inventory audits, and ensuring compliance with asset tracking policies. Annette needs the ability to update the Asset tag field, but for accountability and audit purposes, management wants this capability granted through a dedicated group rather than a direct role assignment.

Your task is to create a new group called "HHD Asset Taggers," assign the u_hhd_asset_tagger role to this group, and add Annette Frietas as a member. This structure provides clear documentation of who has asset tagging privileges and makes it easy to add or remove asset taggers in the future.

Task Objectives
1. With the security_admin role, create a new HHD Asset Tagger group with the following:
- Group Name: HHD Asset Taggers
- Add Role: u_hhd_asset_tagger
- Add Group member: Annette Frietas
4.9 Test the Asset Tag field
Lesson
After implementing security controls, thorough testing is essential to confirm they work as intended. Impersonation provides a safe, non-disruptive method to validate access controls by temporarily viewing the system through another user's perspective. This simulation combines impersonation with field-level ACL testing to verify that your security configuration correctly restricts and permits access to the Asset tag field based on role membership.

Scenario
You've completed a comprehensive security implementation for HHD asset tag management:
- Created the u_hhd_asset_tagger role.
- Configured a field-level write ACL on the Asset tag field requiring this role.
- Established the HHD Asset Taggers group with the role assigned
- Added Annette Frietas as the sole member of this group.
Before announcing this new security model to the organization, you need to verify it works correctly.

Specifically, you must confirm that:
1. Regular HHD users cannot modify asset tags: Beth Anglin is a member of the Service Desk group with the u_holographic_handheld_hhd_user. role. She should be able to create HHD records, but the Asset tag field should be read-only (grayed out) for her.

2. Asset taggers can modify asset tags: Annette Frietas should have full access to create HHD records AND edit the Asset tag field because she's a member of the HHD Asset Taggers group.

Your task is to impersonate both users, test the Asset tag field accessibility on the HHD form, verify the security controls work as designed, then properly end impersonation and de-elevate your security_admin role.

Task Objectives

This task requires you to impersonate another user. You must end the impersonation before selecting Show hint or Validate task.

1. With the security_admin role: 
- Impersonate Beth Anglin.
- Navigate to the HHD application and verify the Asset tag field is read-only (greyed out) on a new record.

2. Impersonate Annette Frietas:
- Navigate to the HHD application and verify Annette has access to all the modules and can write on the Asset tag field.

3. Remove the security_admin role from the logged in user.


